I"›<p>The purpose of HTML tags is to deliver <strong>meaning</strong> to a document. Donâ€™t be concerned about how your webpage looks like. Focus on the significance of each tag youâ€™ll use.</p>

<p>Depending on the content youâ€™re writing, you can choose the appropriate element that matches the meaning of your text.</p>

<p>This <strong>range</strong> of elements is wide enough to both accomodate for <strong>general</strong> purpose matter (like paragraphs or lists), and more <strong>specific</strong> content like <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;output&gt;</code> (to display the result of a calculation) or <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;progress&gt;</code> (to display the progress of a task).</p>

<h3 id="structure-elements-organizing-your-page">Structure elements: organizing your page</h3>

<p>Structure elements allow you to organize the <strong>main parts</strong> of your page. They usually contain other HTML elements.</p>

<p>Hereâ€™s what a typical webpage could include:</p>

<ul>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;header&gt;</code> as the <strong>first</strong> element of the page, that can include the logo and the tagline.</li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;nav&gt;</code> as a list of <strong>links</strong> that go to the different pages of the website.</li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code> as the title of the page.</li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;article&gt;</code> as the main content of the page, like a blog post.</li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;footer&gt;</code> as the <strong>last</strong> element of the page, located at the bottom.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="text-elements-defining-your-content">Text elements: defining your content</h3>

<p>Inside these structure elements, you usually find <strong>text</strong> elements meant to define the <strong>purpose</strong> of your content.</p>

<p>Youâ€™ll mainly use:</p>

<ul>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;p&gt;</code> for paragraphs</li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;ul&gt;</code> for (unordered) lists</li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;ol&gt;</code> for (ordered) lists</li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;li&gt;</code> for individual list items</li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;blockquote&gt;</code> for quotes</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="inline-elements-distinguishing-your-text">Inline elements: distinguishing your text</h3>

<p>Because text elements can be long but with varied content, <strong>inline</strong> elements allow to <strong>distinguish</strong> parts of your text.</p>

<p>There are a lot of inline elements available, but youâ€™ll usually come across the following:</p>

<ul>
  <li><code>&lt;strong&gt;</code> for <strong>important</strong> words</li>
  <li><code>&lt;em&gt;</code> for <em>emphasized</em> words</li>
  <li><code>&lt;a&gt;</code> for <a href="#">links</a></li>
  <li><code>&lt;small&gt;</code> for <small>less important</small> words</li>
  <li><code>&lt;abbr&gt;</code> for abbreviations like <abbr title="World Wide Web Consortium">W3C</abbr></li>
</ul>

